<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="472" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,608,1715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Description.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[494,582,680,707]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
, body shape ovate. Dorsal side, antennae and legs uniformly coloured brown without colour pattern or metallic shine, surface without distinct setation. Head with small punctures, sparser on clypeus, surface finely shagreened. Clypeal membrane not exposed. Male head at genae with a pair of broad, short, glabrous, and bifurcated processes pointing upright. Eyes small, distinctly globose. Antennae (
<figureCitation box="[1198,1265,788,814]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[307,1292,231,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[196,1391,179,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Dorsal view of male species of Micropeneta Pic, 1921 (all in SMNS). 1. M. kinabaluca sp. n., holotype. 2. M. alabaca sp. n., holotype. 3. M. excavatifrons Pic, 1921, non-type. 4. M. papuana sp. n., holotype. 5. M. sodalis Bremer, 1997, non-type. 6. M. laotica sp. n., holotype. 7. M. leytica Schawaller, 1994, holotype. 8. M. tarandus (Kaszab, 1946), non-type. Scale bar: 3 mm." pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) 10-segmented with 4-segmented club. Pronotum widest across middle, 1.9x as wide as long, anterior angles rounded and protruding, posterior angles rectangular, lateral margins regularly rounded, broadly beaded, with fine dentation, posterior and anterior margins finely beaded; surface of pronotum dull, shagreened, with fine punctures similar to those on head, anterior part of male pronotum with broad medial impression, anterior margin without teeth; prothoracic hypomera without punctures, surface smooth and feebly shagreened; prosternal apophysis somewhat protruding backwards. Elytra ovate, surface shining, 0.9x as wide as long, widest across middle, with large punctures regularly arranged in rows, punctures distinctly larger than pronotal punctures, diminishing in posterior part of elytra, intervals with a row of fine punctures; lateral margins with fine dentation and visible in dorsal view nearly over complete length of elytra, humeral angles not pronounced; epipleura diminishing somewhat before apex, with a few scattered small punctures, punctures smaller than those on metasternum. Hind wings absent. Abdominal ventrites with fine punctures smaller than those on elytra, last visible ventrite 5 not beaded and without modifications. Legs without specific characters, anterior tibiae triangular, with external keel prolonging to the distal angle, and internally with a brush of light hairs, middle and posterior tibiae rounded in cross section and externally without any keels. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1234,1301,1256,1282]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–13" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[153,1422,188,1080]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1435,181,1085]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9–13. Aedeagus of species of Micropeneta Pic, 1921 (all in SMNS). 9. M. alabaca sp. n., holotype. 10. M. laotica sp. n., holotype. 11. M. papuana sp. n., holotype. 12. M. sodalis Bremer, 1997, non-type. 13. M. kinabaluca sp. n., holotype. Scale bar: 1 mm." pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) with broad triangular apicale with rounded apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="472" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,608,1715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1328,1354]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Schawaller &amp; Bellersheim, 2022" authorityName="Schawaller &amp; Bellersheim" authorityYear="2022" box="[327,565,1328,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Micropeneta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alabaca" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[327,565,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Micropeneta alabaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[571,633,1328,1354]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[571,633,1328,1354]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be recognised by the shape of the pair of broad, short, and bifurcated processes on the male head, by the male pronotum anteriorly with distinct impression but anterior margin without medial teeth, by the pronotum with lateral margins strongly rounded and broadly beaded, by the pronotum with shagreened surface, and by the distinct regular elytral rows of punctures. 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" box="[966,1376,1436,1462]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Micropeneta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excavatifrons">
<emphasis box="[966,1264,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Micropeneta excavatifrons</emphasis>
Pic, 1921
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[307,1292,231,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[196,1391,179,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Dorsal view of male species of Micropeneta Pic, 1921 (all in SMNS). 1. M. kinabaluca sp. n., holotype. 2. M. alabaca sp. n., holotype. 3. M. excavatifrons Pic, 1921, non-type. 4. M. papuana sp. n., holotype. 5. M. sodalis Bremer, 1997, non-type. 6. M. laotica sp. n., holotype. 7. M. leytica Schawaller, 1994, holotype. 8. M. tarandus (Kaszab, 1946), non-type. Scale bar: 3 mm." pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) has also the male pronotum anteriorly with a broad impression, but the male head armature is shorter and only tubercle-like and not bifurcated, and the pronotal disc between punctures is shining. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bremer &amp; Ferrer, 1994" authorityName="Bremer &amp; Ferrer" authorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Micropeneta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mjoebergi">
<emphasis box="[1086,1347,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Micropeneta mjoebergi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bremer, H. J. &amp; Ferrer, J." pageId="1" pageNumber="472" pagination="15 - 18" refId="ref5121" refString="Bremer, H. J. &amp; Ferrer, J. (1994) Eine neue Micropeneta - Art aus Borneo (Col., Tenebrionidae, Gnathidiini). Acta Coleopterologica, 10, 15 - 18." type="journal article" year="1994">Bremer &amp; Ferrer, 1994</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[384,480,1544,1570]" name="Malaysia" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Sarawak</collectingCountry>
has a similar armature on the male head as 
<taxonomicName authority="Schawaller &amp; Bellersheim, 2022" authorityName="Schawaller &amp; Bellersheim" authorityYear="2022" box="[966,1093,1544,1570]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Micropeneta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alabaca" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[966,1093,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">M. alabaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1099,1162,1544,1570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1099,1162,1544,1570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but has additionally the anterior margin of the male pronotum with a pair of distinct, narrowly situated teeth, and the pronotum is widest before middle with the anterior angles not protruding (according to figures in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bremer, H. J. &amp; Ferrer, J." box="[1055,1319,1616,1643]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" pagination="15 - 18" refId="ref5121" refString="Bremer, H. J. &amp; Ferrer, J. (1994) Eine neue Micropeneta - Art aus Borneo (Col., Tenebrionidae, Gnathidiini). Acta Coleopterologica, 10, 15 - 18." type="journal article" year="1994">Bremer &amp; Ferrer 1994</bibRefCitation>
). See also identification key below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1246,1688,1715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,608,1715]" box="[199,1246,1688,1715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1688,1714]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named after Gunung (= Mt.) Alab, in whose vicinity the 
<typeStatus box="[982,1080,1688,1714]" pageId="1" pageNumber="472">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected.
</paragraph>
